    You should have received a copy of the GNU General Public License along
    with this program; if not, see the file COPYING in this directory.


Provenance
----------

The upstream is id Software's `linuxdoom-1.10` source, released by John Carmack
on 1997-12-23. That original 1997 release was published under the "DOOM Source
Code License", a non-commercial-use license. id subsequently relicensed the
same source under the GNU General Public License, version 2. The GPL-2
relicensing — not the 1997 license — is what permits this port to exist and be
redistributed here.

Two artifacts of that history look like contradictions and are not:

  1. The per-file headers in the `linuxdoom-1.10` C sources still read "only
     under the terms of the DOOM Source Code License as published by id
     Software". id never rewrote those headers when they relicensed. The
     operative grant is the LICENSE.TXT shipped alongside them, which is the
     GPL-2 text, and the README.TXT, which closes with "Copyright (c) ZeniMax
     Media Inc. / Licensed under the GNU General Public License 2.0." The stale
     headers do not narrow that grant.

  2. Consequently the GPL-2 headers on the `.bet` files in this directory are
     *not* transcriptions of the C originals' headers. They are the standard
     GPL-2 notice, applied to reflect the license the code is actually under.

`COPYING` is a byte-identical copy of the `LICENSE.TXT` that id ships with the
DOOM source. It is the older Free Software Foundation revision of GPL-2 (the
"59 Temple Place" address, and "Library" rather than "Lesser" General Public
License). Its operative terms are identical to the current gnu.org revision;
only the FSF's mailing address and that rename differ. It is reproduced as id
shipped it rather than swapped for the newer revision.

The grant is version 2 specifically. id and ZeniMax state "the GNU General
Public License 2.0" with no "or (at your option) any later version" clause, so
the notices here do not claim one.


Copyright attribution within this directory
-------------------------------------------

Every `.bet` file here is part of one GPL-2 combined work and carries the GPL-2
notice. The copyright lines differ by file, deliberately:

  * Files translated from id's C sources carry both id Software's copyright and
    the translator's. Most of this directory is in this category — including the
    `defs/` modules, which are translations of id's headers under new names
    (`defs/player.bet` from `d_player.h`; `defs/think.bet` from `p_mobj.h`,
    `d_think.h` and `p_pspr.h`; `defs/fixed.bet` from `m_fixed.c`; and so on).

  * Files that are this port's own original work carry only the translator's
    copyright. These are the `tools/` test harnesses and the music subsystem
    (`s/opl.bet`, `s/mus.bet`, `s/genmidi.bet`, `s/wad.bet`) — an OPL2 FM
    synthesizer, a DMX MUS sequencer, a GENMIDI bank parser, and a standalone
    WAD directory walk. `linuxdoom-1.10` contains none of these: Linux DOOM had
    no music and shelled out to an external `sndserv` for audio. They are GPL-2
    because they are part of this combined work, not because they derive from
    id's code.

Attributing id's copyright to files id did not write would be a false copyright
statement, which is why this split exists rather than a blanket header.


Game data
---------

No copyrighted WAD data is committed to this repository, and none of it is
covered by the GPL. The GPL-2 release covers id's *source code* only; the DOOM
game assets remain proprietary to id/ZeniMax and are not redistributable.

Run this port against the shareware `doom1.wad` (freely redistributable, and
the source of the DEMO1/2/3 lumps used as the correctness oracle), against a
commercial IWAD you own, or against Freedoom (BSD-licensed).

See ../../LICENSING.md for how this GPL-2 directory relates to the Apache-2.0
`bet` language and toolchain that surround it.
